author: Michelle Coffey
title: 12 of the most compelling Apollo moon mission images from among the 8,400 posted to Flickr
text:
NASA/Project Apollo Archive Slide 1 of 13 Over 8,400 high-resolution photographs captured during NASA’s Apollo moon landings have been released on Flickr, featuring every single image taken by astronauts.
The Project Apollo Archive’s collection features stunning views of Earth, the American flag on the moon’s surface and the iconic moonwalks, and it delves into the everyday minutiae of each mission: food packets, shaving cream and sleeping masks.
See all the Project Apollo Archive space images on Flickr
Kipp Teague, the archivist who compiled the photos for the Project Apollo Archive , told the Planetary Society that every picture ever taken on the moon with the Hasselblad cameras or while in orbit has been included in the collection. Teague said the pictures are unprocessed, taken from original NASA photo scans, with some of them comparable to the washed-out images you might come across while flipping through an old family photo album.
See also: How Matt Damon could rocket NASA to Mars in real life
